        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 🏢 Data Structure\n",
        "\n",
        "### 🏗️ Different Data Structures\n",
        "\n",
        "- Often two data sets can have the same semantics but [different data structures]{.accent}.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Data structures can be broadly categorized into two types:\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.columns}\n",
        ":::{.column width=\"50%\"}\n",
        "- [Wide data structure]{.accent}:\n",
        "    - One row per subject.\n",
        "    - Repeated measurements are in separate columns.\n",
        ":::\n",
        ":::{.column width=\"50%\"}\n",
        "- [Long data structure]{.accent}:\n",
        "    - One row per measurement.\n",
        "    - There is a column identifying which variable was measured\n",
        ":::\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.fragment}\n",
        "\n",
        "![Long vs Wide Data Structures](assets/long-vs-wide.png){width=\"40%\"}\n",
        "\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## ↔️ Wide Data Structure\n",
        "\n",
        "### Let's build some intuition...\n",
        "\n",
        "- To build our intuition let's create a copy of the data set used by [Luke Bennett](https://www.thedataschool.co.uk/luke-bennett/long-vs-wide-data-tables/).\n",
        "    - The data set contains the points, assists and rebounds of 4 basketball teams.\n",
        "    - ❓ Have a go at making this dataframe in python using `pd.DataFrame`.\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.fragment}"
      ],
      "id": "0fdb20e7"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| echo: false\n",
        "#| tbl-cap: \"Basketball Data Set\"\n",
        "\n",
        "basketball_data = pd.DataFrame({\n",
        "    \"team\": [\"A\", \"B\", \"C\", \"D\"],\n",
        "    \"points\": [88, 91, 99, 94],\n",
        "    \"assists\": [12, 17, 24, 28],\n",
        "    \"rebounds\": [22, 28, 30, 31]\n",
        "})\n",
        "basketball_data.set_index(\"team\")"
      ],
      "id": "b0789957",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "- Each observation (team) is on its own row.\n",
        "- Each observation has multiple variables in separate columns.\n",
        "\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## ↕️ Long Data Structure\n",
        "\n",
        "### What is a long data structure?\n",
        "\n",
        "- What would this data look like in a long data structure?\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.fragment}"
      ],
      "id": "e3dd6d22"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| echo: false\n",
        "\n",
        "basketball_data_long = basketball_data.melt(id_vars=[\"team\"], var_name=\"statistic\", value_name=\"value\")\n",
        "basketball_data_long.sort_values(by=\"team\").iloc[0:6,:].set_index(\"team\")"
      ],
      "id": "6261dd85",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "- We observe now that:\n",
        "    - Each measurement has its own row (`value`)\n",
        "    - There is a column identifying which variable was measured (`statistic`)\n",
        "\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## Long vs Wide Data Structure\n",
        "\n",
        "### 🤔 Which is better?\n",
        "\n",
        "- Wide data is more [human-readable]{.accent}:\n",
        "    - Common in spreadsheets\n",
        "- Long data is more [computer-readable]{.accent}:\n",
        "    - Required by most plotting libraries (`seaborn`, `ggplot` in `R`)\n",
        "    - Easier to [filter]{.accent}, [group]{.accent}, and [aggregate]{.accent} in `pandas`.\n",
        "- It is therefore important to be able to [convert between the two data structures]{.accent}.\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.fragment}\n",
        "\n",
        "### Code to build the basketball data set"
      ],
      "id": "8c2e5467"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| echo: true\n",
        "#| eval: false\n",
        "basketball_data = pd.DataFrame({\n",
        "    \"team\": [\"A\", \"B\", \"C\", \"D\"],\n",
        "    \"points\": [88, 91, 99, 94],\n",
        "    \"assists\": [12, 17, 24, 28],\n",
        "    \"rebounds\": [22, 28, 30, 31]\n",
        "})"
      ],
      "id": "97be442a",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## `pd.melt`\n",
        "\n",
        "### `pd.melt` - Wide → Long\n",
        "\n",
        "- `pd.melt` is a function that converts a wide data structure to a long data structure.\n",
        "- It takes the following arguments:\n",
        "    - `id_vars` are the columns that identify the subject.\n",
        "    - `var_name` is the name of the column that will contain the variable names.\n",
        "    - `value_name` is the name of the column that will contain the variable values.\n",
        "\n",
        "<br>\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.fragment}"
      ],
      "id": "d159b259"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "output-location": "column-fragment"
      },
      "source": [
        "#| echo: true\n",
        "#| eval: true\n",
        "\n",
        "# Wide → Long\n",
        "basketball_data_long = basketball_data.melt(\n",
        "    id_vars=[\"team\"], \n",
        "    var_name=\"statistic\", \n",
        "    value_name=\"value\"\n",
        "    )\n",
        "print(basketball_data_long)"
      ],
      "id": "08b868c1",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## `pd.pivot`\n",
        "\n",
        "### `pd.pivot` - Long → Wide\n",
        "\n",
        "- `pd.pivot` is a function that converts a long data structure to a wide data structure.\n",
        "- It takes the following arguments:\n",
        "    - `index` is the column that will contain the subject identifiers.\n",
        "    - `columns` is the column that will contain the variable names.\n",
        "    - `values` is the column that will contain the variable values.\n",
        "\n",
        "<br>\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.fragment}"
      ],
      "id": "1974b7aa"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "output-location": "column-fragment"
      },
      "source": [
        "#| echo: true\n",
        "#| eval: true\n",
        "\n",
        "# Long → Wide\n",
        "basketball_data_wide = basketball_data_long.pivot(\n",
        "    index=\"team\", \n",
        "    columns=\"statistic\", \n",
        "    values=\"value\")\n",
        "print(basketball_data_wide)"
      ],
      "id": "7cc11b22",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## Lack of Standard Format\n",
        "\n",
        "### Which do you prefer?\n",
        "\n",
        "- Difficult to say why one layout might be preferable.\n",
        "    - Most data is stored in a layout that made [intuitive sense to the creator]{.accent}.\n",
        "    - 🙂‍↔️ [Idiosyncratic]{.accent} and [unprincipled]{.accent}.\n",
        "    - Few widely used conventions\n",
        "    - Lots of variability 'in the wild'\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.fragment}\n",
        "\n",
        "### Consequences for Data Scientists\n",
        "\n",
        "- Data scientists must determine how best to [reorganize datasets]{.accent}.\n",
        "- Broadly, this involves two [interdependent choices]{.accent}:\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.columns}\n",
        ":::{.column width=\"50%\"}\n",
        "- Choice of [representation]{.accent}: how to encode information.\n",
        "    - Dates as one or three variables?\n",
        "    - Use values 1, 2, 3 or 'low', 'med', 'high'?\n",
        ":::\n",
        ":::{.column width=\"50%\"}\n",
        "- Choice of [form]{.accent}: how to display information\n",
        "    - Wide table or long table?\n",
        "    - One table or many?\n",
        ":::\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## What's the solution?\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.columns}\n",
        ":::{.column width=\"50%\"}\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.spacer-sm}\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "### 🧹Tidy Data Standard\n",
        "\n",
        "- Data scientists introduced the [tidy data standard]{.accent} to help solve the problem of inconsistent data structures.\n",
        "\n",
        "- It has two main advantages:\n",
        "    - Facilitates workflow by establishing a consistent dataset structure.\n",
        "    - Principles are designed to make transformation, exploration, visualization, and modeling easy.\n",
        "\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.column width=\"50%\"}\n",
        "\n",
        "<br>\n",
        "\n",
        "![Tidy Data Standard](assets/cleaning.gif)\n",
        "\n",
        ":::\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "# Tidy Data\n",
        "\n",
        "## Tidy Data Principles\n",
        "\n",
        "### What is tidy data?\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.fragment}\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.emphasize}\n",
        "\"Tidying your data means storing it in a consistent form that matches the semantics of the dataset with the way it is stored. In brief, when your data is tidy, each column is a variable, and each row is an observation. Tidy data is important because the consistent structure lets you focus your struggle on questions about the data, not fighting to get the data into the right form for different functions.\" - Wickham and Grolemund, R for Data Science, 2017.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.fragment}\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.spacer-sm}\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "### Tidy = Semantics and Structure\n",
        "\n",
        "- A dataset is a collection of values which is said to have:\n",
        "    - [Semantics:]{.accent} Meaning of each value\n",
        "    - [Structure:]{.accent} How values are arranged\n",
        "- The [tidy standard]{.accent}: data semantics $\\leftrightarrow$ data structure\n",
        "\n",
